explanation:
For checking reachability you must know which calls/macros can cause early returns, non-returning behavior, or conditional guards that make subsequent code unreachable. Explanations: 
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: macro can expand to an early return, longjmp, abort, or other control-flow that makes the rest of the function unreachable when timer_prop is NULL. Its exact expansion is required. 
- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl: called to get objtype; if it does not return or can cause an early exit/assert, that affects reachability of the subsequent if/return and the rest of the function. 
- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: passed into OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl; its behavior (returning or not) influences whether the objtype comparison is reachable. 
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE: constant used in the objtype comparison; needed to determine when the immediate return (OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE) is taken. 
- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE: the return value used when the objtype test is true; needed to know function exits there. 
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: controls whether the main body inside if(return_code == OS_SUCCESS) is reachable; may also have non-standard control-flow (assert/abort). Its possible return values are required. 
- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB: arguments to OS_ObjectIdGetById; their meanings can affect behavior/valid return paths of that call. 
- OS_SUCCESS: value compared against return_code; needed to decide whether the guarded block is reachable. 
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro used to obtain records from tables; macro expansion could include checks/early returns or side effects that affect reachability. 
- OS_global_timecb_table, OS_timecb_table, OS_timebase_table: tables used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; their definitions/availability affect whether the code that dereferences them (and so the block) is valid/reachable. 
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: called at the end of the success path; if it has non-returning behavior it affects reachability analysis of code after it (though in this function nothing follows, but its behavior is still relevant for control-flow assumptions). 
- OS_timer_prop_t, OS_common_record_t, OS_timecb_internal_record_t, OS_timebase_internal_record_t: type/layout definitions are required to understand the accesses inside the success branch (memset, strncpy, field reads). They also let an analyzer determine whether any of those accesses could cause undefined behavior that would make code effectively unreachable.

These symbols are the minimal set required to determine whether any branch or statement in OS_TimerGetInfo can never be reached (i.e., to decide actual reachability of the early returns and the guarded success block).
